==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*fara-'', from Indo-European ''*per-''.  Germanic cognates include Old Frisian [[fara]], Old Saxon ''faran'' (Dutch [[varen]]), Old High German ''faran'' (German [[fahren]]), Old Norse [[fara]] (Swedish [[fara#Verb|fara]]), Gothic [[𐍆𐌰𐍂𐌰𐌽]].  The IE root is also the source of Greek [[περαν]], Latin [[portare]], Slavic ''*pьratī'' (Old Church Slavonic [[перѫ]], Russian [[переть]]).

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'faɹan/

===Verb===
(ġe)'''faran''' (class VI strong)
# to [[go]], to [[travel]]
#:''Nu wylle ic faran'': Now I will go.

